# Mos DSL Grammar

## Root-level block types

A `.mos` file starts with a root block: `contract`, `sprint`, `rule`, `specification`, `need`, `architecture`, `config`, `lexicon`, `binder`, `batch`, `doc`, `directive`, `watch`.

Inside root blocks the parser accepts: **fields** (`key = value`), **named blocks** (`name { ... }`), and **keyword blocks** (`section`, `scope`, `config`, `harness`, `feature`, `spec`, `criterion`).

## Feature blocks

`feature "Name" { ... }` — only three child types allowed:

| Child | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `background { ... }` | Shared preconditions (at most one) |
| `scenario "Name" { ... }` | Gherkin-style acceptance criterion |
| `group "Name" { ... }` | Logical grouping of scenarios |

**Nothing else is valid inside feature.** No `description = "..."`, no free-form fields. Put descriptive text in the feature's name string instead.

```
feature "Guard API: single entry point for all enforcement" {

  scenario "pre-commit delegates to guard" {
    given = "A project root"
    when  = "guard.PreCommit(root) is called"
    then  = "Returns unified pass/fail with diagnostics"
  }
}
```

## Scenario blocks

`scenario "Name" { ... }` accepts:

- `given = "..."` / `when = "..."` / `then = "..."` — Gherkin triple
- `labels = [...]` — string array for tagging
- Any `key = value` field

## Spec blocks

`spec "Name" { ... }` accepts `include "path"` directives and `feature` blocks.

## Rule files

`rule "slug" { ... }` — mechanical rules require at least one of: `feature`, `spec` with includes, or `harness` block.

```
harness {
  command = "go build ./..."
  timeout = "30s"
}
```

## Lifecycle statuses by artifact type

| Type | Active | Terminal (archive) |
|---|---|---|
| contract | `draft`, `active` | `complete`, `cancelled`, `abandoned`, `closed`, `duplicate` |
| sprint | `planned`, `active` | `complete`, `closed`, `abandoned`, `duplicate`, `cancelled` |
| specification | `candidate`, `draft`, `active` | `superseded`, `retired` |
| need | `identified`, `validated`, `addressed` | `retired` |
| batch | `planned`, `ready` | `promoted`, `cancelled` |

Artifacts in terminal status belong in `archive/`, not `active/`.
